abstract: Yesterday, the Sunday-schools of Hunter's Point celebrated their anniversary. It was the intention to form in procession at their churches, Methodist and Baptist, and march to Burden's Grove, but on account of the rain this part of the programme was changed, and the scholars, together with their friends, assembled at the new Baptist Church where, with music, short addresses and ice-cream and strawberries, the time passed pleasantly.

abstract: EZRA PRIME, a prominent and influential resident of Huntington, was removed to the Insano Asylum, Bloomingdale, on Monday. Mr. PRIME, for a number of days, has been showing symptoms of insanity, and has been under the charge of friends for the past week. His idiosyncracies have been both amusing and dangerous. At one time he was advising how to rid the world of criminals, and at anothor fighting every one who came near him.

abstract: The supplementary elections in France absorb all attention, and a heated contest is waged between the Republican and the Monarchist journals. The former are united, but the latter, although most numerous, are weakened by dissensions. The idea is entertained of forming a second Chamber to be elected by the Councils-General. Denunciation of Communists continues, and many arrests are made daily. The members of the International Society are distributing electoral manifestoes.

abstract: The session of the Ecclesiastical Court, on Dr. LANAHAN'S trial, was resumed yesterday morning at 10 o'clock. abstract: PARIS, June 23.--A letter from M. LOUIS BLANC is published, declaring that the Republican party, hitherto a force, must become a power. The Libert reports that a violent quarrel took place yesterday on the Boulevards between the promenaders and a party of Prussian officers. In consequence of the affair Marshal McMAHON has requested the Prussian commander to prevent his officers from entering the city.

abstract: On Friday night, Mrs. COOK, of Hoboken, undertook to improve a sluggish fire by pouring kerosene on it from a can. The contents of the vessel exploded, blowing off her thumb and spreading the blazing liquid all over her person. abstract: The dream of an ocean pier at Long Branch is about to be realized. Engineers are now upon the ground selecting a location. The pier will be of iron, 1,200 feet long, and throughout the first 1,000 feet it will be 30 feet wide. The last 200 feet will have a width of 100 feet, and on it will be a pavillion and parlors having accommodations for 2,000 persons.

abstract: A subscription paper is being circulated in Flushing, among the merchants and business men, for the purpose of securing a steam fireengine for the village. It is understood that the trustees will pay the expense of running the machine, and accept a new fire company which it is proposed to organize, to have charge of the engine. The cost of it will be $3,000, about onehalf of which has been pledged.
